<section id="about">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Our Sacred Heritage</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">A Sanctuary of <em>Faith & Peace</em></h2>
    <div class="about-grid">
      <div class="about-text fade-in">
        <p>The <strong>Gurudwara Sikh Temple Estate</strong> of Chittagong stands at Chowk Bazar in the heart of the city, on the right bank of the <strong>Karnaphuli River</strong>. It is one of the most historically significant Sikh shrines in all of Bangladesh, and a spiritual landmark of immeasurable importance.</p>
        <p>The site commemorates the visit of the founder of Sikhism, <strong>Guru Nanak Dev Ji</strong>, who is believed to have halted here around <strong>1507–08 CE</strong> on his great spiritual journeys across Asia. During his stay, he held religious discourses, converted local followers, and preached the message of One God and universal brotherhood.</p>
        <p>The Gurudwara was originally established as a <em>Manji</em> (a Sikh meeting place) by Bhai Jhanda, a devoted carpenter who became one of Guru Nanak's earliest disciples in this region. The current building was completed in <strong>1830</strong>, renovated in 1971–72 after Bangladesh's liberation, and further preserved in 1988–89.</p>
        <p>An ancient well adjoining the temple — still in use today — is believed to date back to the time of the Guru's visit, a living relic of this holy site's extraordinary age.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="stats-strip">
