<section id="history">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Through the Ages</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">A <em>Living Chronicle</em> of Devotion</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">c. 1507–08 CE</div>
        <div class="timeline-event">Guru Nanak's Sacred Visit</div>
        <div class="timeline-desc">Guru Nanak Dev Ji halts at Chittagong on his great spiritual journey. He holds religious discourses at Chowk Bazar, preaching the gospel of One God and universal brotherhood. A devoted carpenter named Bhai Jhanda becomes his first disciple here. Later, Prince Indra Sen and King Sudhar Sen also accept the Guru's teachings.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">c. Early 1600s</div>
        <div class="timeline-event">Manji Established — Bhai Natha</div>
        <div class="timeline-desc">A missionary named Bhai Natha, who had come to Dhaka during the time of the 6th Sikh Guru, establishes the Manji (Sikh meeting place) at the Chowk Bazar site, formalising it as a centre of Sikh worship in Bengal.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">1740–1756</div>
        <div class="timeline-event">Bhai Mohan Singh's Endowment</div>
        <div class="timeline-desc">Bhai Mohan Singh, a Sikh who rose to become Diwan (Revenue Minister) of Nawab Ali Vardi Khan of Bengal, donates substantial property to the Gurudwara. The Nawab makes the endowment rent-free, ensuring the shrine's maintenance.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">1830</div>
        <div class="timeline-event">The Temple Building Completed</div>
        <div class="timeline-desc">After a period of neglect and gradual rebuilding, the Gurudwara's main building is completed in 1830. It continues to serve as the principal Sikh place of worship in the Chittagong region.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">1917</div>
        <div class="timeline-event">Committee Management Formed</div>
        <div class="timeline-desc">Following the death of the last Udasi mahant, the District Judge of Chittagong forms an 11-member management committee — a system that continues to this day under the Bangladesh Gurdwara Management Committee.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">1971–72 &amp; 1988–89</div>
        <div class="timeline-event">Renovation &amp; Preservation</div>
        <div class="timeline-desc">After Bangladesh's liberation, essential repairs are carried out. A further full renovation is undertaken in 1988–89 with contributions from Guru Nanak's followers across Bangladesh and the world, including construction of an outer verandah for the building's protection.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

