    <div class="khanda">☬</div>
    <div class="section-label">The Founder of Sikhism</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Guru Nanak <em>Dev Ji</em></h2>
    <div class="guru-card fade-in">
      <div class="guru-info">
        <h3>Birth &amp; Early Life</h3>
        <p><strong>Guru Nanak Dev Ji</strong> was born on 15 April 1469 in the village of Talwandi (now Nankana Sahib, Pakistan) to a Hindu family. From childhood he displayed remarkable wisdom and spiritual insight, astounding his teachers with deep knowledge. By age 16, he was fluent in Sanskrit, Persian, and Hindi. He rejected the caste system, empty rituals, and idol worship from a young age, and championed the dignity and equality of women.</p>
        <h3>Spiritual Awakening &amp; The Udasis</h3>
        <p>At age 28, Guru Nanak had a profound spiritual awakening at the Bein River and proclaimed: <em>"Na koi Hindu, na koi Musalman"</em> — "There is no Hindu, there is no Muslim" — declaring God's oneness beyond all religious divides. He then undertook four great journeys (Udasis) from 1500 to 1524, travelling across India, Tibet, Arabia, and Persia, accompanied by his devoted companion <strong>Bhai Mardana</strong>. It is during these journeys that he visited Chittagong.</p>
        <h3>His Message to the World</h3>
        <p>Guru Nanak's teachings are enshrined in the sacred scripture <strong>Guru Granth Sahib Ji</strong>. He contributed 974 poetic hymns, emphasising God's oneness, equality of all humankind, rejection of discrimination, and a life of selfless service. He established <strong>Langar</strong> — the community free kitchen — as a living symbol of equality, where all sit together regardless of caste, faith, or status.</p>
        <h3>His Legacy at This Shrine</h3>
        <p>This very Gurudwara commemorates the Guru's blessed stay in Chittagong. His encounter with Bhai Jhanda, Prince Indra Sen, and King Sudhar Sen transformed this city into a seat of Sikh faith in Bengal. <strong>Guru Nanak Dev Ji passed away on 22 September 1539</strong> in Kartarpur, leaving behind a faith that today has over 30 million followers worldwide.</p>
